y in America couldn't the following be amended to the constitution. When the original was drafted, firearms were muzzle-loaders. It follows that, if civilians could only own such weapons, this would significantly reduce such outrages. This should keep both the gun loonies and constitution buffs happy.</p><p>I also seem to recall something about a citizens' militia? Why couldn't such people be required to report once a week for training (head-shaving, etc), and if they are so keen, they could also be posted to Afghanistan. I speak with some experience having lived in America for some time – indeed, 20 years ago, I was delivered an eviction order by two men carrying guns.<br /><strong>Clive Wilkinson</strong><br /> <em>Leamington Spa, Warwickshire</em></p><p></p><p>• Your editorial (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2012/dec/16/americans-gun-control-newtown-editorial\" title=\"\">The shots heard round the world</a>, 17 December) talks rightly of the need to strengthen gun control and of how powerful the gun lobby is in the US. But you end with the comment: \"Mad men with guns will always be a danger.\" This is a lazy stereotype and, indeed, early reports about the killer suggest he may have had a learning disability. It is guns that are the problem and perhaps mental health provision does need to improve, but it is simply not the case that having a mental illness will lead to such a tragedy.<br /><strong>Ruth F Hunt</strong><br /><em>Burscough, Lancashire</em></p><p></p><p>• My daughter teaches in Blacksburg, Virginia, the site of the massacre at Virginia Tech in 2007. She asked her class of 9- and 10-year-olds recently who&nbsp;had at least one gun in their home. All but three raised their hands and all three of those exceptions were not born&nbsp;in the US.<br /><strong>EL Trussell</strong><br /><em>Sudbury, Suffolk</em></p><p></p><p>• How good of David Cameron to express his sympathy for the victims of the Newtown massacre. I wonder how many Pakistani and Afghan children will have to be murdered by British and US remote-controlled drone operators before he'll feel it's worth expressing sympathy for them as well?<br /><strong>Tony Green</strong><br /><em>Ipswich, Suffolk</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/401229387|2012-12-22T11:49:03Z|fc62e4a42be5da3624b518d1f6a52256922167cc -->","showInRelatedContent":"true","strap":"Letters","lastModified":"2012-12-18T00:00:35Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","score":"1.0","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3ct6m","wordcount":"493","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"401229387","internalOctopusCode":"7034110","isPremoderated":"false","publication":"The Guardian","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-12-18","internalPageCode":"1843825","shouldHideAdverts":"false","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-12-20T21:00:04Z"},"tags":[{"id":"world/gun-control","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webTitle":"US gun control","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gun-control","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/gun-control","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/editorialsandreply","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webTitle":"Editorials & reply","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/mainsection/editorialsandreply","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/editorialsandreply","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/mainsection","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"news","sectionName":"News","webTitle":"Main section","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/mainsection","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection","references":[]},{"id":"tone/letters","type":"tone","webTitle":"Letters","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone/letters","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/letters","references":[]},{"id":"world/newtown-shooting","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","